ng to neglect discourses and results from the other. Contrary to a verdict of strict segregation between "is" and "ought," there are, nowadays, various attempts to integrate both theoretical approaches. This calls for a discourse on the relation between empirical research and normative theory. In this volume, scholars from different disciplines – including psychology, sociology, economics, and philosophy – discuss the possible desired or undesired influences on, and limits of, the integration of these two approaches.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 4aEmpirische Theorie. 4aNormative Theorie. 4aSein-Sollen-Dichotomie. 4aWerturteil. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aIs-ought dichotomy.  aempirical research and evidence.  ainterdisciplinary perspectives.  anormative theory.1 aAgostini, Maximilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Alexander Max, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIngo Meyerhuber, Malte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJasso, Guillermina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonow, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKreienkamp, Jannis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKunz, Marvin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatos Fernandes, Carlos A. de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMax Bauer, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMertz, Marcel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeyerhuber, Malte, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeyerhuber, Sylke, econtributor.4ctb4https:/